      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nTimekeeping is present in all peoples due to its importance for our lives.\n\nIn this text, we will explore two methods of timekeeping that have been used by different peoples throughout history: one based on the Sun and another based on the Moon (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nBefore exploring these calendars, a reflection is warranted:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "736b2d0a-62b5-466a-bedb-74ba12752ae5",
                     "text": "Llyas, M.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1994",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad027885-dbe9-4eb3-9b00-7524d19439c9",
                     "text": "Aslaksen, H.",
                     "page": "pp. 3 - 13",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: All Correct</b><br /><br />Do all calendars currently in use correctly represent the Earth's orbit around the Sun?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_week",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Week\n\nThe possible origin of the week has already been analyzed in a previous text (<htcite0>); therefore, we will not discuss it again here. However, there is one fact we must revisit, as it will aid us in our studies. When we speak of a week, we are referring to a period of 7 days; thus, we use the multiplication table of seven in sequence to assist us.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b504be6f-2380-4319-add3-c0682c07e886",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Our Week",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent7\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_gregorian",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### The Gregorian Calendar\n\nHumanity has created different calendars according to their beliefs and needs. Some of these are available in History Tracers, at the top right, making it easier to read content according to the calendars we are accustomed to in our daily lives.\n\nIn this section, we will discuss the Gregorian calendar.\n\n#### The Shortest Month in the Gregorian Calendar\n\nAccording to the Gregorian calendar, the month of February has 28 days in most years, but has 29 days every four years, in a year known as a leap year (<htcite0>).\n\nLooking at the multiplication table for 7, we can see that 28 is divisible by 7. That is, it is possible to have an exact number of weeks in that month, as shown in **Calculation 1**:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "adf021de-1c26-44d7-a243-b47eac246c61",
                     "text": "Britannica Editors",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table style=\"width: 30%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; font-weight: none; border-collapse: collapse;\"><tr><td>&nbsp; <span style=\"color: blue;\">28</span> </td><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black; border-left: 2px solid black;\"> 7 </td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black;\">-  <span style=\"color: blue;\">28</span> </td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 0 </td><td> &nbsp; </td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Division of 28 by 7.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### The Other Months\n\nAs a consequence of **Calculation 1** and, especially, the multiplication table for 7, any month containing between 29 and 31 days cannot have exactly 4 full weeks.\n\nLet's take an example of a 31-day month:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table style=\"width: 30%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; font-weight: none; border-collapse: collapse;\"><tr><td>&nbsp; <span style=\"color: blue;\">31</span> </td><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black; border-left: 2px solid black;\"> 7 </td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black;\">-  <span style=\"color: blue;\">28</span> </td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3 </td><td> &nbsp; </td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Division of 31 by 7.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Observe that by performing **Calculation 2**, we confirm there are 3 days more than the 28 days that 4 weeks have.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgAstro\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgAstro', '0%')\" src=\"images/BritshMuseum/mid_00437459_001.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Astrolabe showing a calendar with the months in Latin, held in the British Museum. © Trustees of the British Museum (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('9dfc0a42-23c6-4e5d-bd99-bd5f39af7b0a'); return false;\"><i>The British Museum</i></a> ).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_arab",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Islamic Calendar\n\nUnlike the Gregorian calendar, the Islamic calendar is a lunar calendar not based on the seasons (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nAmong the characteristics relevant to this study, the following stand out (<htcite2>):\n- The months have 29 or 30 days;\n- The year has 354 or 355 days;\n- There are four consecutive months with 30 days;\n- There are three consecutive months with 29 days;\n- A new month begins whenever a new crescent moon is visible.\n\n#### Weeks\n\nArabs have also used weeks to group days since the first century of their calendar (the 7th century of the Gregorian calendar) (<htcite3>).\n\nThus, we can also verify the number of weeks in the months of the Islamic calendar (**Calculations 3 and 4**)",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad027885-dbe9-4eb3-9b00-7524d19439c9",
                     "text": "Aslaksen, H.",
                     "page": "pp. 10",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "736b2d0a-62b5-466a-bedb-74ba12752ae5",
                     "text": "Llyas, M.",
                     "page": "pp. 425 - 427",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1994",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "736b2d0a-62b5-466a-bedb-74ba12752ae5",
                     "text": "Llyas, M.",
                     "page": "pp. 427 - 428",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1994",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "96f1335a-b88b-44b0-aa36-052daec52f9b",
                     "text": "Zerubavel, E.",
                     "page": "pp. 25 - 26",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1989",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table style=\"width: 30%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; font-weight: none; border-collapse: collapse;\"><tr><td>&nbsp; <span style=\"color: blue;\">29</span> </td><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black; border-left: 2px solid black;\"> 7 </td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black;\">-  <span style=\"color: blue;\">28</span> </td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1 </td><td> &nbsp; </td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculations 3</b>: Division of 29 by 7.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table style=\"width: 30%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; font-weight: none; border-collapse: collapse;\"><tr><td>&nbsp; <span style=\"color: blue;\">30</span> </td><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black; border-left: 2px solid black;\"> 7 </td></tr><tr><td style=\"border-bottom: 2px solid black;\">-  <span style=\"color: blue;\">28</span> </td><td>4</td></tr><tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2 </td><td> &nbsp; </td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculations 4</b>: Division of 30 by 7.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Given that the Islamic months have exactly the same length as some Gregorian months, one would expect the Islamic months to also have four weeks plus some days (remainders 1 and 2). However, there is another aspect we need to explore through a reflection.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: The Century...</b><br /><br />When observing different calendars around the world—which can be accessed at the top right of <i>History Tracers</i>—we can realize that the centuries are not the same among them.<br /><br />Has it ever crossed your mind that mentioning only the century, without stating which calendar is used, constitutes incomplete information?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
